{% call components.section("Pattern 3: Sticky card") -%}

  <p>The sticky card pattern is a single page or cross-page offer that persists on the side of the screen.</p>

  <h3>Design</h3>

    <p>The sticky card can hold a resource type, title and CTA. It can function in a couple of different ways depending on the primary goal of the page:</p>

    <p><strong>Less interruptive</strong>: on pages where the primary goal is to support reading and learning the card will fade-in to view after the visitor has scrolled 1000 pixels on the page. It will be fixed so that it follows the visitor down the page. On mobile the sticky card will be shown inline on the page. For example, we show a less interruptive card on article pages.</p>

    <p><strong>More interruptive</strong>: on pages where the primary goal is to present the visitor a personalized offer, the card will animate in from the right once the visitor has scrolled past the hero. On mobile the sticky card will be shown as an overlay, the same as on desktop. For example, show this on pages after a visitor has taken action that indicates they have interest in a certain subject in order to present a resource or event they may be interested in.</p>

    <div class="margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
        <img src="{{ '/assets/sticky-card/sticky-card.svg' | url }}" alt="Sticky card" style="--inline-img-max-width: 271px;">
    </div>

  <h3>How to use</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>The sticky card should promote a resource or event, only allowing for a label, title and CTA. </li>
    <li>This pattern can be used on a single page or across a set of pages. </li>
    <li>This is useful on pages that do not have a CTA in the hero or near the top of the page as it can be used to call attention to a personalized primary resource.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The audience</h3>
  
  <ul>
    <li>This card can be displayed to site visitors who have shown interest in a product or topic, but have not converted.</li>
  </ul>

