{% call components.section("Pattern 5: In-page card") -%}

  <p>The in-page card pattern utilizes an existing card or cards within a page for personalization or targeting.</p>

  <p><em>Note: cards are templated in Adobe Target only on the homepage of redhat.com. For a different card experience on other pages, new design and development work may be required.</em></p>

  <h3>Design</h3>

    <p>There are several versions of in-page offer cards depending on what type of asset you need to promote.</p>

    <p>The examples are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Resource offer</li>
      <li>Event/webinar offer</li>
      <li>Page offer</li>
      <li>Product card</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="margin-top--4 margin-bottom--4">
        <img src="{{ '/assets/card/card.svg' | url }}" alt="Card" style="--inline-img-max-width: 360px;">
    </div>

  <h3>How to use</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>Find an existing card or cards within your page or set of pages you want to personalize.</li>
    <li>Define the offer you’re trying to promote (event, webinar, announcement, press release).</li>
    <li>To automate the process for what you’re showing to the user, Adobe has pre-built technology to automatically personalize based on a user’s attributes or an algorithm based on content type. Please work with the Digital Systems team if you’re interested in this direction.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>The audience</h3>

  <p>An in-page card should be relevant to the context of the page the user is currently on.</p>

