{% call components.section("Pattern 6: Active tab") -%}

  <p>The active tab pattern is a simple experience applicable to any page that contains tabs. This pattern aims to customize visitor experience by highlighting a tab based on visitor’s interests.</p>

  <h3>Design</h3>

    <p>The active tab pattern uses the existing tab design, only customizing the active tab within the tabset. No custom design work is needed.</p>

    <div class="margin-top--10 margin-bottom--4">
        <img src="{{ '/assets/tabs/tabs-theme-light.svg' | url }}" alt="Tabs" style="--inline-img-max-width: 872px;">
    </div>

  <h3>How to use</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>Choose your target audience</li>
    <li>Choose the tab that best aligns to that audience in order to provide a targeted experience to them</li>
    <li>Request the active tab experience be set for that audience, describing what goals you hope to accomplish by doing so.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>The audience</h3>

  <p>An active tab design can be used for the following types of content (among others):</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Persona-based targeting</li>
    <li>Lifecycle-based targeting</li>
    <li>Product affinity targeting</li>
    <li>Topic affinity targeting</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Get started with the announcement banner</h3>

  <ol>
    <li>identify a page or set of pages that have tabs on them that would be ideal for targeting a specific audience.</li>
    <li>Choose which tab aligns to which audience.</li>
    <li>Describe your KPIs for a successful experience (i.e. activating the cloud product tab on the homepage tabset for a cloud product affinity resulted in XX% higher clickthrough rates to products)</li>
    <li>Submit questions concerning user experience to the Digital Systems UX team: digital-systems-web-team@redhat.com</li>
  </ol>

{%- endcall %}

